question: Let $\mathbf{a} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ \sqrt{\pi} \\ -14 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} -1 \\ 3 \\ 10 \end{pmatrix}.$  Compute $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}).$
answer: The vectors $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ are always orthogonal, so their dot product is $\boxed{0}.$
agents_response:
To find $\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b}$ we first need to find the cross product of $\mathbf{a}$ and $\mathbf{b}$. The cross product is given by:
\[\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} \mathbf{i} & \mathbf{j} & \mathbf{k} \\ 4 & \sqrt{\pi} & -14 \\ -1 & 3 & 10 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -3\sqrt{\pi} - 122 \\ -46 + 10\sqrt{\pi} \\ 13\sqrt{\pi} - 7 \end{pmatrix}.\]
Then, we compute $\mathbf{a} \cdot (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b})$:
\[\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ \sqrt{\pi} \\ -14 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} -3\sqrt{\pi} - 122 \\ -46 + 10\sqrt{\pi} \\ 13\sqrt{\pi} - 7 \end{pmatrix} = -12\pi - 488 - 46\pi + 140 - 182 + 98 = \boxed{-58\pi - 250}.\]
